'''Metallibure''' ({{abbrlink|INN|International Nonproprietary Name}}) (brand names '''Aimax''', '''Suisynchron''', '''Turisynchron'''; former developmental code names '''ICI-33828''', '''AY-61122''', '''NSC-69536'''), also known as '''methallibure''' ({{abbrlink|USAN|United States Adopted Name}}, {{abbrlink|BAN|British Approved Name}}) or '''methallibur''' ([[German language|German]]), is a medication which was introduced in 1973 and has been used in [[veterinary medicine]] to synchronize [[estrus]].<ref name="Elks2014">{{cite book|author=J. Elks|title=The Dictionary of Drugs: Chemical Data: Chemical Data, Structures and Bibliographies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0vXTBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA781|date=14 November 2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4757-2085-3|pages=781–}}</ref><ref name="Gordon2013">{{cite book|author=I. Gordon|title=Controlled Breeding in Farm Animals|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mEgvBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313|date=22 October 2013|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-1-4832-8569-6|pages=313–}}</ref> It was [[withdrawn drug|withdrawn]] in the [[United States]] and [[Europe]] due to [[teratogen]]icity and has been replaced with [[altrenogest]] (Regumate, Matrix), a [[progestin]].<ref name="Gordon2013" /><ref name="pmid19848281">{{cite journal | vauthors = Brüssow KP, Schneider F, Kanitz W, Rátky J, Kauffold J, Wähner M | title = Studies on fixed-time ovulation induction in the pig | journal = Soc Reprod Fertil Suppl | volume = 66 | issue = | pages = 187–95 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19848281 | doi = | url = }}</ref>
The precise [[mechanism of action]] of metallibure is unknown.<ref name="Gordon2013" /> It has been described as a "[[nonsteroidal]] [[antigonadotropin]]" and it appears to act directly on the [[pituitary gland]] and/or [[hypothalamus]] to suppress [[gonadotropin]] [[secretion]].<ref name="Gordon2013" /> However, metallibure has also been reported to be an [[antiprogestogen]] and to act specifically via [[enzyme inhibitor|inhibition]] of the [[biosynthesis]] or [[secretion]] of [[progesterone]].<ref name="Labhart2012">{{cite book|author=A. Labhart|title=Clinical Endocrinology: Theory and Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DAgJCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA523|date=6 December 2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-642-96158-8|pages=523–}}</ref>
Metallibure has similar [[endocrinology|endocrinological]] effects in women.<ref name="JUCKER2013">{{cite book|author=JUCKER|title=Progress in Drug Research / Fortschritte der Arzneimittelforschung / Progrès des recherches pharmaceutiques|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y8HzBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|date=21 December 2013|publisher=Birkhäuser|isbn=978-3-0348-7065-8|pages=102–}}</ref> It is associated with several unpleasant [[side effect]]s including [[anorexia (symptom)|appetite loss]], [[nausea]], occasional [[vomiting]], [[lethargy]], and [[drowsiness]].<ref name="JUCKER2013" /> Animal [[toxicity]] studies revealed that the medication induced the development of [[cataract]]s, and this resulted in the termination of its [[clinical development]].<ref name="JUCKER2013" />
